          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In the old days, th=
e Hollywood issue was published a month in advance of the Academy Awards as=
 a prelude to the brand=E2=80=99s inimitable Oscar night party, once the mo=
st exclusive event on the global social calendar. Of course, things have ch=
anged. Now, the <i>VF </i>party is a plum sales item for the matrixed Cond=
=C3=A9 Nast sales team, and the Hollywood issue apparently arrives at the v=
ery forefront of awards season rather than its conclusion. Alas, the cover =
doesn=E2=80=99t cast quite the same spell as in the halcyon <b>Annie Leibov=
itz </b>era=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CReigning Men=E2=80=9D in 2003, or the all-fema=
le ensemble in 2016, from <b>Jane Fonda </b>to <b>JLaw</b>=E2=80=94but it w=
as fine, if straightforward. It could have doubled as a Gucci advertisement=
, with the backdrop rendered in designer <b>Sabato</b> <b>De</b> <b>Sarno</=
b>=E2=80=99s favorite<i> ancora</i> red. The <b>George</b>
<b>Cortina</b>-styled contenders include <b>Nicole</b> <b>Kidman</b>, <b>De=
v</b> <b>Patel</b>, <b>Glen</b> <b>Powell</b>, and <b>Zoe</b> <b>Salda=C3=
=B1a</b>. <b>Zendaya</b> was born to wear Ala=C3=AFa, <b>Josh</b> <b>O=E2=
=80=99Connor</b> was born to show off his green eyes, and yes, many folks (=
slash brand ambassadors) were apparently destined to wear Gucci. <br/><br/>=
Someone involved in the preliminary discussions insisted that Jones=E2=80=
=99 team had long pined for the scheduling change. Publishing the issue at =
the beginning of the awards cycle would make it easier to book cover talent=
 (editors would no longer have to game out which stars might <i>actually </=
i>get nominated so many months in advance) and demonstrate that the magazin=
e still has influence with Academy voters. It also inevitably offered a lar=
ger yield of For Your Consideration clients=E2=80=94a subset of the adverti=
sing market that <i>VF </i>has grown increasingly dependent on in recent ye=
ars. <br/><br/>But some other skeptics of
Cond=C3=A9 Nast C.E.O. <b>Roger</b> <b>Lynch</b>=E2=80=99s strategy refuted=
 the notion that this timing change was being pushed by editorial. Rather, =
they speculated, the move was done to short-sightedly boost revenue for 202=
4, which is down, once again, in the U.S. and also globally. <br/><br/>Perh=
aps both theories are true. I=E2=80=99m told that the editorial team has tr=
ied to convince the sales force that the Hollywood Issue and the Oscar Part=
y should not necessarily be sold hand-in-hand, even if that doesn=E2=80=99t=
 quite make economic sense. =E2=80=9CThe point of the party is the Oscars,=
=E2=80=9D as one person close to the company told me. =E2=80=9CThe point of=
 the Hollywood Issue is Hollywood=E2=80=94which is the Oscars. Is <i>Vogue<=
/i>=E2=80=99s September Issue going to be in March now?=E2=80=9D <br/></td>
